[{'comment_id': 465367433, 'comment_body': "Since we intend to support 3 SCMs: `github`, `gitlab`, and `bitbucket` and be agnostic, we can use

https://github.com/screwdriver-cd/ui/blob/32d16fa559dac66f8f064a8e45d5a557a0b75a18/app/application/controller.js#L22

```
session: service(),



const currentContext = session.get('data.authenticated.scmContext');
```", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 4, 22, 33, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adong', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465833811, 'comment_body': "sure! I'll get it fixed", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 16, 0, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'supra08', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465888981, 'comment_body': "`autoKeysGeneration: DS.attr('string'),`

Should this default to `''` empty string?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 17, 29, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adong', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465889020, 'comment_body': "From: https://github.com/screwdriver-cd/ui/pull/568/files#diff-6b06326e0cb4622d4b9dfc45401cd687R34
```
      autoKeysGeneration: snapshot.attr('autoKeysGeneration') || false
```

Does `autoKeysGeneration: false` imply `DS.attr('boolean')` 🤔 ?

I see `autoDeployKeyGeneration` is `DS.attr('boolean')` already, what is the difference between `autoDeployKeyGeneration` vs `autoKeysGeneration`?

To me `autoKeysGeneration` is the expected payload that API expects, while `autoDeployKeyGeneration` is the actual string from user's input?
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 17, 29, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adong', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465890462, 'comment_body': "If we change the default value from `false` to `''`, also need to update test here :)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 17, 32, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adong', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465984203, 'comment_body': 'Oh my bad, it should be boolean only. 
Actually from the UI and API side, the flag dealing with this is `autoKeysGeneration` only. `autoDeployKeysGeneration` is the flag that the user sets in the config and what is fetched in the scm modules after parsing the config.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 20, 27, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'supra08', 'type': 'User'}]

catch log and respond error part of API payload, so that UI can display.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 14, 30, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jithine', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465770853, 'comment_body': "is this feasible ? isn't this a new pipeline creation ?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 14, 31, 34, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jithine', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465771281, 'comment_body': 'is pipelineFactory.scm & userFactory.scm referring to same ?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 14, 32, 11, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jithine', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465820098, 'comment_body': 'Yeah I guess I can use userFactory for both.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 15, 40, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'supra08', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465873742, 'comment_body': "is this needed ? won't the `addDeployKey` promise reject ?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 17, 3, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jithine', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465904610, 'comment_body': 'This boolean check if scm, such as `github` has ability to do `autoKeysGeneration`.

What if such scm, say `bitbucket` does not have such feature and `autoKeysGeneration = true` from the payload. How do we handle that case? Would there be: 

1) add a `catch` block
2) add another if condition to check both payload sent from ui has `autoKeysGeneration: true`, as well as check if given SCM has such ability.

In UI, we can prevent user giving input for if scm does not have `autoKeysGeneration` feature, but we also need to sanitize and guard on API. I can see some power users would call this API directly.


Just a thought, what do you think?


Note: 

From: https://github.com/screwdriver-cd/screwdriver/issues/1079#issuecomment-393631839

If we apply this feature to all SCMs: `scm-github`, `scm-bitbucket`, then we dont have such issue, just need to catch the errors.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 5, 17, 57, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adong', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465970936, 'comment_body': "Yeah a catch should have been used. I'll correct it.

```suggestion
            autoDeployKeyGeneration: false # [Optional] Set to true to allow automatic generation of private and public deploy keys and add them to the build pipeline and Github, respectively
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 20, 54, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tkyi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 468180558, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
* Enable automatic generation and handling of deploy keys as a part of the pipeline by setting the `autoDeployKeyGeneration` flag to `true` in their `config/local.yaml`. With this flag enabled, the user will get an option to actually trigger the generation in the UI.
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 20, 55, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tkyi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 468839268, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
            autoDeployKeyGeneration: false # [Optional] Set to true to allow automatic generation of private and public deploy keys and add them to the build pipeline and Github for repo checkout, respectively
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 11, 20, 17, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tkyi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 468840670, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
Deploy Keys are SSH keys that grant access to a single GitHub repository. This key is attached directly to the repository instead of to a personal user account, as opposed to Github personal access tokens. Github personal access tokens give user-wide access for all the repositories while deploy keys, on the other hand, give access to a single repository. pr_title: feat(1415): Add alternate routes and handlers for subscribed repos
pr_body:
## Context

Fixes screwdriver-cd/screwdriver#1415

## Objective

This PR adds handlers for using the subscribed config. If the parsed config contains the `subscribe` object it is formatted to convert scmUrl to scmUri mapped with their actions. This mapped array is used by the modified addWebhook() method (now addMultipleWebhooks()) to add the webhooks along with the corresponding actions.

Now when a webhook request arrives in the screwdriver API, it identifies it whether it is external and captures is `checkoutUrl`. The API filters the triggered pipelines based on the `checkoutUrl`. Further in the `eventFactory`, it needs to be figured whether the job(s) is(are) triggered or not. This is done by performing a `breadth-first-search` of the `workflowGraph` with `~subscribe` as the root node. This way all the dependant jobs are identified wrt the triggered jobs, `workflowGraph` updated and build started.

## References

screwdriver-cd/screwdriver#1415

## License

## Objective

This PR adds logic to webhook endpoint to handle notifications from external repos. First it filters the triggered pipelines with the checkoutUrl from the incoming request. After that it is checked whether the request is from an external repo or not and based on that sends a flag to the EventFactory module to handle them likewise.

pr_title: feat(scm-github): Allow editing of existing PR bot comments
pr_body:
## Context

Fixes screwdriver-cd/screwdriver#1714

## Objective

Before this, when multiple builds took place, it resulted in multiple meta PR comments. To tackle that, the comments for that PR is listed and if a bot comment is found, it is edited, else a new comment is created.

## References

screwdriver-cd/screwdriver#1714

## License
